# Operation Modes

Every request to the {{ROLE_TERM}} resolves to one operating mode. There are **six lifecycle modes** that follow the research loop, and **two cross-cutting modes** that orchestrate or maintain it. Plain question-answering is the default and is not a mode.

Read this file when the task mode is ambiguous. Classify first, then act under that mode's discipline. Startup order is mastered by `docs/entrypoint.md`. Each mode links to its own protocol file (lifecycle modes in the table below, cross-cutting modes in section 2); this page is the router and the at-a-glance contract.

## 1. Lifecycle Modes

| Mode | Purpose | Seat & safety | Protocol |
|---|---|---|---|
| Investigate | Gather **external / existing** knowledge: literature, prior work, methods, web search, and reading the current codebase. | Chat · read-only (reaches external services) | `docs/operations/investigate-mode.md` |
| Design | Generate hypotheses and approaches, and plan the next {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}}. | Chat · read-only | `docs/operations/design-mode.md` |
| Implement | Create or change code and specifications. | Code · mutating | `docs/operations/implement-mode.md` |
| Experiment | Run an experiment **and record its results** back into the docs (ingestion is the closing step of this mode). | Code · mutating + compute cost | `docs/operations/experiment-mode.md` |
| Analyze | Draw conclusions from the project's **own** artifacts, **including critical verification** of those conclusions. | Chat / Code · read-only | `docs/operations/analysis-mode.md` |
| Write | Produce README, technical report, or paper prose. | Chat · mutating (docs only) | `docs/operations/write-mode.md` |

Boundary between the two read-only research modes: **Investigate** brings in information from outside the project (or surveys code you have not yet internalized); **Analyze** reasons over results and artifacts the project already produced.

## 2. Cross-Cutting Modes

These are not lifecycle steps; they sit above or alongside the loop.

<!-- if:ENABLE_AUTO_MODE=yes -->
- **Auto** — autonomously chain the lifecycle modes toward a goal, inside hard safety boundaries (isolated workspace, fixed budget, explicit stop conditions). Auto-running the read-only modes (Investigate, Design, Analyze) is low-risk; auto-running Implement or Experiment **must** use an isolated workspace and never edit existing files in place. Auto returns proposals for Write and Maintain rather than performing them autonomously. See `docs/operations/auto-mode.md`.
<!-- endif -->
- **Maintain** — keep the project healthy: docs consistency and large-scale cleanup, plus the reflection ritual that turns failures into prevention rules (operational constraints and {{ANALYSIS_RECORD_LABEL}}s). See `docs/operations/maintenance-mode.md`.

## 3. Trigger Classification

| The request is about... | Mode |
|---|---|
| "what does prior work do", "find a paper / method", "search the web", "read the codebase" | Investigate |
| "what should we try next", "propose an approach", "design the next {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}}" | Design |
| "write / change the code", "implement the spec" | Implement |
| "run it", "train / evaluate", "record the result" | Experiment |
| "what do these results mean", "is this real", "verify / stress-test the claim" | Analyze |
| "draft the README / report / paper section" | Write |
<!-- if:ENABLE_AUTO_MODE=yes -->| "explore this autonomously", "run a campaign for N hours" | Auto |<!-- endif -->
| "clean up the docs", "reflect on what went wrong", "turn this lesson into a rule" | Maintain |

If a request mixes modes, decompose it: do the read-only modes first (Investigate / Design / Analyze), confirm the plan with {{USER_NAME}}, then enter a mutating mode.

Example (illustrative). "The new approach is not beating the baseline -- figure out why and fix it" decomposes into: **Analyze** (why it underperforms, with critical verification) -> confirm the diagnosis -> **Design** (the corrective change) -> **Implement** it -> **Experiment** (run and record). Five modes, surfaced as a short plan before any file changes -- not one undifferentiated "fix it" pass.

## 4. Mode Discipline And Safety

- **Read-only vs mutating is a hard property.** Read-only modes (Investigate, Design, Analyze) and any auto-run of them must not change tracked files outside `${CLAUDE_DIR}/{TASK_ID}/`. Mutating modes (Implement, Experiment, Write, Maintain) state their edit scope up front.
- **Doc-update is every mode's closing discipline**, not a separate mode: when a mode produces a durable result, cascade it into the docs per `docs/operations/consistency-guard.md` and run `make docs-check`.
- **Judgment is an output, not a mode.** A verdict (accept / inconclusive / reject; see the verdict vocabulary in `docs/evaluation/evaluation-and-visualization.md`) is the result of Analyze or Experiment, recorded in `docs/project/project-status.md`.
- **Project Instructions** changes are surfaced as candidate text for {{USER_NAME}} to paste (see `docs/operations/project-memory-and-instructions.md`); they are not a mode and are never edited silently.
- **Default Q&A** (a quick question answered in 1-3 lines) needs no mode.

## 5. Common First Move

Whatever the mode: read `docs/entrypoint.md`, summarize the current state, pull only the task-relevant docs, classify the mode, verify code/paths/numbers against current files, and state the edit scope before changing anything. Lead chat answers with the conclusion in {{CHAT_LANG}}.

## 6. If The Mode Was Wrong

If the mode changes midstream: state the mismatch in one sentence, reclassify, decide whether existing artifacts are kept, and if it matters, capture a {{ANALYSIS_RECORD_LABEL}} or an operational constraint via Maintain mode.
